DIABETES CLASSIFICATION USING LOGISTIC REGRESSION 

INTRO:
The objective of this project is to build a machine learning model to predict whether a person has diabetes or not.
The dataset contains several medical predictor variables such as glucose level, BMI, blood pressure, and age.
Logistic regression is used as the classification algorithm.

PROCESS I HAVE FOLLOWED:
at first i ve imported libraries like numpy ( which helps me to do the mathematical calculation earier ) ,
 pandas (this is for data handling),and matplotlib (is for give the shape like ploting diagram and grafh and flowchart)
 then seaborn is used for statistical data visualization

dataset description:
The dataset used is the Diabetes Dataset obtained from Kaggle. It contains medical data of patients. The dataset has 
768 rows and 9 columns.
The target variable is Outcome, where:
0 → Non-diabetic
1 → Diabetic
You can list features like:
Pregnancies
Glucose
BloodPressure
SkinThickness
Insulin
BMI
DiabetesPedigreeFunction
Age
Outcome
The dataset was explored using pandas functions such as .info(), .describe(), and .shape() to understand its
structure and statistical properties.
The dataset was checked for zero values using (df == 0).sum(). Certain medical attributes such as Glucose,
BloodPressure, SkinThickness, Insulin, and BMI contained zero values which are not realistic. These values 
were treated as missing data and replaced with NaN using the replace() function.
NaN means Not a Number, which represents missing data.Fills missing values.Calculates the mean (average) of each column.
inplace=True ,This means the changes are applied directly to the dataset.Dataset cleaned for machine learning.
to keep in mind 0=false means no missing values.
Each "histogram" shows the distribution of data for a specific category. Here’s a quick breakdown of how to read them:
The x-axis (bottom): Represents the value of the metric (e.g., a Glucose level of 100 or 150).
The y-axis (side): Represents the count—how many people in the dataset fall into that specific range.
The "Big Picture": These charts help you spot outliers or skewed data. For example, in your "Insulin" and 
"DiabetesPedigreeFunction" charts, the data is "right-skewed," meaning most people have low values, with only a few 
people having very high values.
The Scale: The values range from -1 to 1.
​1.0 (White/Lightest): A perfect positive relationship. (Notice the diagonal line of 1s? That’s just a variable compared to itself, like Glucose vs. Glucose).
​Near 0 (Dark/Black): No relationship at all. The variables don't seem to affect each other.
​Positive (Red/Pink): As one goes up, the other tends to go up.
​Negative (Minus sign): As one goes up, the other goes down
Looking at your specific heatmap, a few things jump out:
​Glucose vs. Outcome (0.49): This is your strongest predictor. It suggests that as Glucose levels rise, the likelihood of
 a positive diabetes "Outcome" (usually 1) increases significantly.​Age vs. Pregnancies (0.54): This is a very strong
 positive correlation. It makes sense—generally, as age increases, the total number of pregnancies a person might have had also increases.
​BMI vs. SkinThickness (0.54): Another strong link. Usually, a higher Body Mass Index correlates with higher skinfold thickness.
Feature Selection & Standardization
The "Fair Comparison" Step (Standardization)
In your data, Glucose might be 150, but Age is only 30. If you don't change this, the computer will think Glucose is 5 times more important just because the number is bigger.
The Code: (X - X.mean()) / X.std()
The Analogy: It’s like converting different currencies (Dollars, Euros, Yen) into one single currency so you can compare them fairly.
The "Filter" (Sigmoid Function)
Computers are good at math, but they don't naturally understand "Yes" or "No." They understand numbers.
The Code: 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))
The Job: It takes a raw score (like 42.5) and squashes it. If the score is high, it turns into 0.99 (99% chance of diabetes). If it’s low, it turns into 0.01 (1% chance).